1. Libraries and datasets

I chose 2 ChIPseq human datasets for the following transcription factors:

  • ESR1: a ligand-activated transcription factor that responds to estrogen (https://www.encodeproject.org/experiments/ENCSR463GOT/).

  • FOXA1: a member of the forkhead class of DNA-binding proteins that acts as a pioneer factor and can also bind to estrogen (https://www.encodeproject.org/experiments/ENCSR126YEB/).

2. ChIPseq analysis

2.1. Overlap of binding sites for the two ChIP-Seq datasets

txdb <- TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg38.knownGene
peak_list <- list(peaks_ESR1,peaks_FOXA1)
names(peak_list) <- c("ESR1", "FOXA1")
vennplot(peak_list)

There are 7059 overlapping peaks for these two ChIPseq datasets. To figure out whether this overlap is bigger than expected by chance, I used âenrichPeakOverlapâ to calculate the significance of the overlap.

enrichPeakOverlap(queryPeak     = "~/Bioinfo_Network/training-requirements/ChIP-Seq Analysis/ESR1.bed",
                  targetPeak    = "~/Bioinfo_Network/training-requirements/ChIP-Seq Analysis/FOXA1.bed",
                  TxDb          = txdb,
                  pAdjustMethod = "BH",
                  nShuffle      = 1000,
                  chainFile     = NULL,
                  verbose       = FALSE)
##    qSample   tSample  qLen  tLen N_OL      pvalue    p.adjust
## 1 ESR1.bed FOXA1.bed 21995 37386 7059 0.000999001 0.000999001

Indeed there is a bigger overlap than expected by chance (adj. p-val << 0.05), which might suggest cooperative regulation.

2.2. Metaplot of the two datasets around the TSS

promoter <- getPromoters(TxDb=txdb, upstream=3000, downstream=3000)
tagMatrix_ESR1 <- getTagMatrix(peaks_ESR1, windows=promoter)
tagMatrix_FOXA1 <- getTagMatrix(peaks_FOXA1, windows=promoter)

plotAvgProf(tagMatrix_ESR1, xlim=c(-3000, 3000), conf = 0.95, resample = 1000)+ggtitle("ESR1")
## >> Running bootstrapping for tag matrix...        2022-06-29 02:45:01 PM

plotAvgProf(tagMatrix_FOXA1, xlim=c(-3000, 3000), conf = 0.95, resample = 1000)+ggtitle("FOXA1")
## >> Running bootstrapping for tag matrix...        2022-06-29 02:45:15 PM

There is an enrichment for ESR1 binding right at the TSS. FOXA1 seems to bind slightly more upstream.

plotDistToTSS(peak_anno_list)

Again here we can confirm that ESR1 binds typically more often close to the promoter and the TSS than FOXA1. FOXA1 binds more often to intronic regions or distal intergenic regions than ESR1.

Both transcription factors regulate genes involved in similar pathways, like âsignaling by receptor of tyrosine kinasesâ, âRho GTPs cycleâ or âNOTCH1 regulated transcriptionâ.

3. Biological interpretation

Both transcription factors that we are analysing here respond to estrogen although they act in a different way. Whereas FOXA1 is a âpioneerâ factor that opens up the chromatin, ESR1 promotes the transcription of target genes. The significant amount of overlapping binding sites that we have identified suggests that in some cases both transcription factors act as a team, with FOXA1 binding first and loosening the chromatin and ESR1 coming second to promote gene expression, and this seems to be supported by previous studies (Theodorou et al., 2012). Therefore, it is not surprising that both transcription factors are involved in regulating genes linked to the same pathways, like âsignaling by receptor of tyrosine kinasesâ or âRho GTPs cycleâ for which there is also previous evidence in the literature (Cavalcanti et al., 2015; Tolias et al., 1995).
